Epistemic Control Systems for Truth‑Convergent Lunar Exploration

PhD Proposal (Version 2.3)
Author: Ouadi Maakoul 
Date: March 26, 2026
Status: Revised with Corrected Theory, Fusion, and Evaluation

---

Executive Summary

Autonomous exploration systems are typically optimized for reward: distance covered, samples collected, or scientific value of visited sites. However, a reward‑maximizing agent can achieve high scores while holding fundamentally incorrect beliefs about its environment—a catastrophic failure mode when decisions affect human safety or resource extraction. We propose a paradigm shift: agents should aim to minimize the distance between their beliefs and the true state of the world. This thesis develops Epistemic Control Systems, a new class of autonomous agents whose primary objective is to reduce uncertainty about an unknown environment.

We provide a rigorous mathematical foundation: we prove that under a policy that maximizes expected information gain (EIG) and a coverage condition that ensures all cells are revisited periodically, the expected posterior entropy decays exponentially, guaranteeing efficient truth‑convergence. We extend this to multi‑agent teams with a robust fusion mechanism—the adaptive logarithmic opinion pool (LogPool)—and prove that it is the information‑geometric centroid of the agents’ beliefs and that its entropy‑based weighting ensures resilience against faulty sensors. We also present a tractable implementation using factored beliefs (occupancy grid mapping) and non‑myopic Monte Carlo tree search (MCTS), with a computational complexity analysis that is feasible for lunar rover hardware.

No physical experiments are presented; instead, this proposal establishes the theoretical underpinnings and system architecture required for future empirical validation.

