2. Research Gap & Contributions

2.1 The Gap

Existing literature in autonomous exploration falls into three categories:

· Reward‑based methods (e.g., coverage maximization, utility‑driven planning) do not guarantee truth convergence.
· Bayesian active learning often assumes a known model or uses myopic information gain without considering long‑horizon planning or multi‑agent coordination under realistic constraints.
· Multi‑agent belief fusion frequently relies on naive product rules that produce overconfident and brittle beliefs, especially when agents have heterogeneous sensors.

No existing framework unifies (i) a purely epistemic objective with proven exponential convergence, (ii) non‑myopic planning via MCTS, (iii) robust multi‑agent fusion with adaptive weights grounded in variational principles, and (iv) lunar‑specific constraints (PSRs, illumination, communication). This gap is the foundation of our thesis.

2.2 Contributions (C1–C4)

Contribution Description Novelty
C1: Epistemic Control Framework Formal definition of agents whose objective is minimizing epistemic error via Expected Information Gain (EIG), with an exponential convergence guarantee in terms of posterior entropy under a coverage condition. First rigorous proof of exponential convergence for EIG‑maximizing policies in discrete POMDP settings, applied to lunar exploration, with explicit coverage‑based \gamma derivation.
C2: Tractable Implementation Factored belief representation (occupancy grid mapping) + non‑myopic MCTS planning for lunar grid worlds, with computational complexity analysis. First integration of non‑myopic EIG planning with a scalable belief representation suitable for real‑time onboard use.
C3: Robust Multi‑Agent Fusion Adaptive Logarithmic Opinion Pool (LogPool) with weights based on sequential marginal likelihood under the prior predictive, proved to be the information‑geometric centroid of beliefs under reverse KL and to have bounded influence of outliers. Extension of opinion pooling theory to heterogeneous rover teams with formal robustness guarantees, with a corrected fusion rule for Bernoulli beliefs.
C4: Theoretical Validation Mathematical proofs of convergence rate, variational optimality, and breakdown point, establishing a benchmark for epistemic performance. First rigorous theoretical analysis of epistemic control in a lunar context.

