4. Problem Formalization & Epistemic Control Framework

4.1 Lunar Grid World Model

We model the lunar environment as a discrete grid of size L \times L (e.g., 20 \times 20). Each cell c has an unobserved binary state \theta_c \in \{0,1\} indicating the presence of a hazard (e.g., water ice, unstable terrain). The ground truth \theta^* \in \{0,1\}^{L^2} is fixed but unknown.

· Action space \mathcal{A}: The rover can move to an adjacent cell (4‑neighborhood) or stay. Later extensions include sensor deployment (e.g., active radar).
· Observation model: When the rover is at cell c, it receives a noisy measurement o \in \{0,1\}:
  P(o=1 \mid \theta_c=1) = \alpha \quad (\text{true positive}), \qquad
  P(o=1 \mid \theta_c=0) = \beta \quad (\text{false positive}),
  with 0 < \beta < \alpha < 1.
· Illumination constraints: Each cell is either illuminated (safe) or permanently shadowed (PSR). Rovers can only recharge in illuminated cells; they must exit PSRs before their battery depletes (modeled as a maximum consecutive steps in shadow).
· Communication: Rovers within a radius R_{\text{comm}} (e.g., 5 cells) can exchange belief summaries. No central fusion center exists; fusion is decentralized.

4.2 Belief Representation: Factored (Cell‑Independent) Model

To achieve scalability, we assume conditional independence between cells: P(\theta) = \prod_{c=1}^{L^2} P(\theta_c). Each P(\theta_c) is a Bernoulli distribution with parameter p_c = P(\theta_c = 1 \mid D_t). This is exactly the occupancy grid mapping representation (Elfes, 1989; Thrun et al., 2005). The update for cell c when an observation o is taken at that cell is:

p_c' = \frac{p_c \cdot \alpha^{o} (1-\alpha)^{1-o}}{p_c \cdot \alpha^{o} (1-\alpha)^{1-o} + (1-p_c) \cdot \beta^{o} (1-\beta)^{1-o}}.

Cells not visited remain unchanged. The entropy of the full belief factorizes: H(P) = -\sum_c [p_c \log p_c + (1-p_c)\log(1-p_c)]. The EIG for an action a can be computed by summing the expected information gain at the cells that will be observed along the path, assuming independence (a standard approximation in active mapping). This makes the planning problem tractable.

While this independence assumption ignores spatial correlations, it is a well‑accepted approximation in robotics and provides a conservative estimate of uncertainty (since correlations would reduce entropy). Future work will incorporate a Gaussian process prior to capture correlations, but the factored model suffices for proving the core concepts and serves as a baseline. The thesis contribution is the planning and fusion framework—the belief representation is modular and can be upgraded without altering the core epistemic control principles.

4.3 Action Selection via EIG‑MCTS

The agent must plan ahead to maximize cumulative information gain. We use Monte Carlo Tree Search (MCTS) with the EIG as the immediate reward. For each candidate action sequence, we simulate future observations using the current belief and evaluate the expected EIG.

· MCTS rollout: Simulate actions up to depth H (e.g., 5–10 steps). At each step, choose actions using a policy (e.g., Upper Confidence Bounds for Trees, UCT) to balance exploration and exploitation of the tree.
· Value function: The value of a node is the cumulative EIG from that node onward, approximated by averaging over simulated futures.
· Non‑myopic planning: By looking ahead, the agent can defer short‑term information gain for a later, more informative observation (e.g., first moving to a recharge point before entering a PSR).
· Simulated observations: During rollouts, observations are sampled from the current belief’s predictive distribution: P(o \mid a, b_t) = \sum_\theta P(o \mid \theta, a) b_t(\theta). This is done per cell and is efficient due to the factored representation.

