5. Multi‑Agent Extension & Robust Fusion

5.1 Decentralized Fusion

Each rover maintains its own factored belief. When two rovers come within communication range, they exchange a compact representation of their belief (the vector of cell probabilities p_i). They then fuse using the adaptive LogPool (C3) with the corrected Bernoulli formula.

Because the belief representation is compact (size O(L^2)), fusion is computationally trivial.

5.2 Adaptive Weight Calculation

We compute weights as the total entropy reduction contributed by each rover over its trajectory. Let \Delta H_i = \sum_c \left( H(p_{i,c}^{\text{initial}}) - H(p_{i,c}^{\text{final}}) \right) be the reduction in entropy achieved by rover i since its deployment. This is a direct measure of epistemic progress and is immune to the self‑reinforcement problem of posterior likelihoods. During communication, rovers exchange their current \Delta H_i and update weights as:

w_i = \frac{\exp(\Delta H_i)}{\sum_j \exp(\Delta H_j)}.

If a rover’s observations are uninformative or its sensor fails, \Delta H_i will be small or negative, and its weight will vanish. This satisfies the robustness property (Theorem 4) while being computationally simple.

