6. System Architecture & Design

The proposed system consists of three main layers:

6.1 Environment Layer

· Simulated lunar grid with static hazards, illumination masks, and communication constraints.
· Sensor noise model.

6.2 Agent Layer

· Belief module: Factored (cell‑independent) representation, updated via Bayes’ rule.
· Planning module: MCTS with EIG as reward (or a value network for faster inference).
· Fusion module: Adaptive LogPool with entropy‑reduction weights for multi‑agent scenarios.

6.3 Evaluation Layer

· Logging of beliefs, actions, and observations.
· Computation of primary metric H(P_t) (posterior entropy) and secondary metrics (\mathcal{E}_t, area under curve, efficiency).

All components are modular, allowing easy substitution of different planning algorithms, fusion rules, or sensor models.

---

7. Simulation Design

7.1 Grid World Specifications

· Grid size: 20 \times 20.
· Hazard probability: 15% (binary), with spatial clustering to mimic real geology (e.g., using a Gaussian random field).
· Sensor: \alpha = 0.85, \beta = 0.15.
· Illumination: PSR mask as a central disk of radius 5 cells.
· Battery: Max 20 steps in shadow before forced exit.
· Communication radius: 5 cells.

7.2 Agents

1. Random: Moves uniformly to a random neighbor (including stay).
2. Greedy Reward: Moves to the cell with highest expected reward, where reward = probability of hazard (based on current belief).
3. Frontier‑based: Moves to the nearest unexplored cell (a standard baseline).
4. Myopic Epistemic: Chooses action that maximizes immediate EIG.
5. Epistemic (MCTS): Uses EIG‑MCTS with horizon 5.
6. Multi‑agent (naive): Two rovers, each using naive product fusion (i.e., p_{\text{fused}} \propto p_i p_j) when in range.
7. Multi‑agent (LogPool): Same but with adaptive LogPool fusion as defined.

7.3 Evaluation Protocol

· Each run: T = 500 steps (to allow convergence).
· 100 independent Monte Carlo runs per agent type.
· Report mean H(P_t) with 95% bootstrap confidence intervals (to account for temporal correlation), and area under the entropy curve (AUC) for aggregate comparison.
· For multi‑agent comparisons, also report robustness metrics: performance under a simulated sensor failure in one rover.

---

8. Evaluation Methodology

Primary hypothesis (H1): Epistemic agents achieve lower H(P_t) (i.e., higher posterior certainty) than reward‑based agents for any t > t_0.

Secondary hypotheses:

· H2: Adaptive LogPool fusion achieves lower H(P_t) than naive product fusion under sensor heterogeneity.
· H3: Multi‑agent teams with LogPool converge faster than single agents, and remain robust to a single faulty rover.

We will use functional comparisons: bootstrap confidence bands for H(P_t) over time, and Mann‑Whitney U tests on AUC values at significance level 0.05. Bootstrap methods are preferred over t‑tests because entropy trajectories are not normally distributed.

