9. Limitations & Future Work

Factored belief assumption: The factored model assumes cell independence, which does not capture spatial correlations. In practice, hazards are spatially clustered (e.g., ice deposits). This may lead to over‑optimistic entropy estimates and suboptimal planning. Future work will extend the representation to Gaussian processes or other spatial models that retain tractability.

MCTS planning horizon: With limited depth, the planner may still be myopic. We will investigate the use of value networks trained from simulation to improve long‑horizon decisions.

Communication bandwidth: The current design assumes rovers exchange full belief vectors. In a real lunar mission, bandwidth is limited; we will explore compressed belief representations (e.g., using low‑rank approximations or variational autoencoders).

Model misspecification: The sensor model is assumed known. We will study the robustness of the approach to model misspecification (e.g., unknown \alpha, \beta).

Safety constraints: In safety‑critical missions, an agent that maximizes information gain might take risks (e.g., entering a PSR with low battery). We will incorporate a safety‑constrained variant where the agent must maintain a minimum energy reserve and avoid entering hazardous areas unless the information gain is deemed sufficiently valuable. This will be modeled as a constrained POMDP and is part of the core design, not future work (see Section 10).

